'''Sequin and Knobel''', or Séquin and Knobel were a Swiss firm of architects notable for the design of industrial building such as [[cotton mill]]s and [[weaving shed]]s. It was formed in 1895. The partners were Carl Arnold Séquin and Hilarius Knobel. Together they were responsible for over 250 industrial buildings.
==Partners==
Carl Arnold Séquin-Bronner (born 25 January 1845 in [[Uznach]]; died 25 November 1899 in [[Rüti ZH]])<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hanak|first1=Michael|title=Séquin, Carl Arnold|url=http://www.hls-dhs-dss.ch/textes/d/D43592.php|website=Historisches Lexikon der Schweiz|accessdate=11 May 2015|language=German}}</ref>
Hilarius Knobel (born 1854 [[Glarus]]; died 1921 [[Zürich]]) was the son of the architect, Hilarius Knobel (born 4 February 1830 in [[Schwändi, near Schwanden, Glarus|Schwändi]]; died 25 February 1891 in Zürich) who was practising in Zürich in 1859.
==Buildings==
*[[Mechanische Baumwollspinnerei und Weberei Augsburg]] (TIM) In 1895/98 they extended the existing factory, by the [[Proviantbach]] in [[Augsburg]], adding a weaving shed for 640 [[power looms|automatic looms]] and a four storey spinning mill containing 42 000 spindles. *Die [[Rote Fabrik]] am Zürichsee ([[Wollishofen|Zürich-Wollishofen]]) *Kammgarn Fabriksgebäude Spinnereistraße 10 in [[Hard, Austria|Hard]], [[Vorarlberg]] {{efn|Fabriksgebäude, Austrian Denkmal ObjektID: 22712, Spinnereistraße 10, Hard, Vorarlberg, Austria: Vorarlberger Kammgarnspinnerei, Fabriksgebäude built from a plan drawn up by C. Sequin, 1896, extended in 1909 by Josef Schöch; single storey steel framed pinning mill.}}
